accessibility.text: Different operating systems use different implementations, interoperability is the characteristic of a product or system whose interfaces are completely understood, to work with other products or systems in either implementation or access without any restrictions.

Syntactic interoperability: if data formats and communication protocols are capable of communicating with each other, they exhibit this type of interoperability. This generally pertains to shared lower-level data formats such as ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
An example of this would be interactions between KaliLinux, Ubuntu and Pop!_OS - they are all forks of Debian Linux and therefore interoperate seamlessly.
Most Posix (Portable Operating System Interface) complaint operating systems achieve interoperability by conforming to a set of API standards.

Semantic interoperability: this type of interoperability is achieved by the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results. An example of this would be loading a web page from a server running CentOS on a Windows computer. This is possible because both use defined communication standards (JSON, XML, HTML, Javascript) to communicate, even though the lower-level implementations are very different.

To improve application usability and reduce development and maintenance expenses, applications should be developed in higher-level, ubiquitous programming languages that either have compilers or interpreters for all operating systems.
